:: April 2000 {"position":"700,850","size":"100,100"}
In April, the CFO created and implemented a credit card policy.  

Later that month, you observe that the petty cash drawers at Enron have never been audited.  The petty cash drawer contains an immaterial amount of cash, but after further investigation, you observe that it is consistently short.  You decide to:

[[Audit Petty Cash]] 

[[Don't Audit Petty Cash]] 




:: Audit Petty Cash {"position":"500,850","size":"100,100"}
This answer is correct.  Auditing petty cash drawers helps improve accountability.  Routinely performing random audits of petty cash is the best practice because it deters theft and being careless with its recordkeeping.  

